I don't feel like machine learning is really "reserved for specialized roles" anymore; most SWEs will interact with big data/AI/ML in one way or another and it's really just another skill to have like Databses, Security, etc.

===================

I'm pretty likely gonna do pure software engineering once I graduate, but I've enjoyed my time in 189 this semester. Cool combination of programming and math!

I don't feel like machine learning is really "reserved for specialized roles" anymore; most SWEs will interact with big data/AI/ML in one way or another and it's really just another skill to have like Databses, Security, etc.

I have started to feel a lot of my friends and people I know are doing the ML track, and I'm curious if it's bad I'm not doing it as well. I was more interested in software engineering as it felt more practical and machine learning felt like it was reserved for specialized roles such as PhD research scientists. I did have some interest, so I watched the webcasts for 189 and old 182, getting a nice high level understanding (commuted a lot on the internship and was pretty fun and educational to do so).

I've taken CS 161, 162, 170, 186, and 188, and was curious are there other people who like the more software engineering side, or just have forgoed the ML track?
history.subject: Is it ok not to take EECS 126, 127, 189?
